{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602061/1937111501/0007.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER. \u20141\n(t) 8. Weather Bureau Forecast.)\nFair and colder tonight; tomorrow The Only evening Paper\nk cloudy and colder, followed by rain, begin- \\X7 a eViim r'4-U li\nning tomorrow afternoon or night: lowest aSninguOn Wltil the\nt temperature tonight, 38 degrees. Temper- Associated PreSS NeWS\natures today\u2014Highest. 50, at 3 p.m.; __ j irt;_i\nlowest, 44, at 5 a m. Full report, page A-12. anfl WirephOtO Services.\nClosing New York Markets, Page )8\n85th YEAR. No. 34.166. post office. Washington mDUcr WASHINGTON, D. 0., MONDAY, NOVEMBER 15, 3937\u2014FORTY PAGES.**** (^*1 Means Associated Press. M'WO CF.NTS\n_______\nAID TO BUSINESS KEYS MESSAGES\nTO CONGRESS; HOUSE MAY FREE\nSMALL FIRMS OF PROFITS LEVYi\nI\nA I\nUltimate Safety\nLies in \u2018Cordial\nCo-operation.\u2019\nBALANCESEEN\nIN \u201938 BUDGET\nFive-Point Plan Is\nUrged as Boon\nto Trade Growth.\nBACKGROUb'D\u2014\nSince President Roosevelt more\nthan a month ago sum moved Con\ngress to special session, a new\nproblem has arisen to worry him\nand the rest of the country\u2014the\nplight of business. Mr. Roosevelt's\nfirst thought for the session was\na series of \"reform\u201d measures, but\nthe course of the stock market and\na growing outburst against restric\ntive business taxes have brought\npressure for a search for some\nmeans of helping the commercial\ninterests ol the. United States.\nBy G. GOULD LINCOLN.\nTaking full cognizance of business\nrecession. President Roosevelt, in his\nmessage to Congress covening today in\nspecial session, said that ultimate\nsafety ljy in a \"cordial anti confident\nen-opera'ion\" between the Govern\nment and \"every' kind\" of citizen and\nTice versa.\nThe President laid before Congress\na preliminary statement of the ad\nministration's intention to come to\nthe aid of business through 'he en\ncouragement, of private (apiral to\nenter wider fiplds. and through the\nremoval of \"unjust provisions\u201d of the\ntax laws.\nNo definite program for business\nrevival was announced. The Presi-\ndent, however, said that a little later\nhe would send another message deal\ning with private capital end housing\non a large scale. He pointed ou* that\nlready the committees of Congress\nend the Treasury are at work on tax\nrevision.\nWhile injustices in the tax laws\n\u25a0hould be removed, the President\nwarned that no amendment should be\nmade which would enable corpora\ntions to avoid paying their fair share\nof the taxes, and that the aggregate\nrevenues of the Government, must be\nkept up.\nBalanced Budget Seen.\nAs a very definite and encouraging\npromise to business and the country\nthe President asserted the Federal\nbudget, for the coming fiscal year\nwould seek a balance between ex\npenditures and revenues. \"A budget\nwhich I expect can be brought within\ndefinite balance.\" the President said.\nThe President, dealt in detail with\nthe specific program of legislation\nwhich he had in mind when he called\nCongress into special session\u2014crop\ncontrol, wages and hours in industry,\nreorganization of the executive branch\nof the Government, and conservation\nof natural and national resources\nthrough the establishment of regional\nT. V. A s.\n\"What these four subjects promise,\u201d\nsaid the President, \"in continued and\nIncreased purchasing power what\nthey promise in greater efficiency in\nthe use of governmental funds\u2014are\nIntelligent foundations for other plans\nfor encouragement of industrial ex\npansion with Government help.\n\"What they promise in social con\ntentment is an almost necessary baV\n(See CONGRESS, Page A-3.)\n\nCONGRESS IS URGED\nTO BOOST BUSINESS\nRepresentative Martin Asks Own\nProgram if President Fails\nto Restore Confidence.\nB? th# Afttoeiftted Pr#ss.\ni Representative Martin. Republican,\nof Massachusetts called upon Con\ngress last night to prepare its own\nprogram for restoration of business\nconfidence if President Roosevelt does\nnot submit \"an integrated program\nOf sound and constructive policies\"\nto the special session which convenes\ntoday.\nThe time has come. Mr. Martin\nsaid in a radio address, for Congress\nto tell America: \"The days of rubber\nstamp legislation are over.\u201d\nMr. Martin, who is chairman of\nthe National Republican Congression\nal Committee, declared that Congress'\nfirst obligation to the worker and\nfanner is to \"restore that full meas\nure of soliu prosperity which has been\nsacrificed by some of the New Deal\nexperimentation.\u201d\nHe advocated \u201creal economy\u201d as\nthe session's watchword.\nAsserting that a large relief roll\nwill be necessary this winter because\nof dismissal of workers in many busi\nnesses. Mr. Martin said the relief\nspending should be \"administered\nhonestly and with rigid efficiency.\u201d\nXakei 22 Chute Jumpi in Bay.\nOKLAHOMA CITY. Nov. 15 (/P).\u2014\nMrs. Paye Lucille Cox. 28. made 22\nparachute Jumps here yesterday.\n1 claiming a world record for consecu\ntive drops In one day.\nI\nText of President\u2019s Message\nNeed for Definite, Early Action for Business,\nLabor and Farm Interests Stressed\nin Document.\nHE text of President Roose- l\nvelt's message to Congress\ntoday follows:\nTo the Congress:\nImportant measures are already\npending before this Congress, and\nother matters will require early\nconsideration. Therefore, it has\nseemed advisable to call this ex\ntraordinary session to expedite the\nwork of the regular session which\nwill begin in January.\nSince your adjournment in\nAugust there has been a marked\nrecession in industrial production\nand industrial purchases following\na fairly steady advance for more\nthan four years.\nWe have not been unaware of\nuncertainties in the economic pic\nture. As far back as last spring\nI called attention to the rapid\nrise in many prices\u2014a rise that\nthreatened in particular the antici\npated revival of building. And over\na month ago I quoted one of the i\ncountry's leading economists to\nthis effect\u2014that the continuance of\nbusiness recovery in the United\nStales depends far more upon busi\nness policies than it doe* upon\nanything that mav be done, or not\ndone, in Washington.\nThe present decline lias not\nreached serious proportions. But\nit ha* the effect of decreasing the\nnational income\u2014and that Is a\nmatter of definite concern.\nDuring the adjournment of the\nCongress I have sought to avail\nmyself of the wisdom and advice\nof managers of large industrial\nand financial enterprise, of owners\n'Continued on Page A-4.)\nD. C. LEGISLATION\nPROGRAM MAPPED:\n\nCivil Service and Budget Bu\nreau to Be Special\nSession Issues.\nChairman Palmisano of the House\nDistrict Committee today mapped out\na tentative legislative program for the\nspecial session of Congress and placed\nin preferred positions legislation that\nwill establish a separate Civil Service\nsystem for municipal employes and\ndivorce the budget bureau and Con\ngress front control over District\nfinances.\nCorporation Counsel Elwood H. Seal,\naccording to Mr. Palmisano, is draft\ning ihe proposed bills and as soon as\nthey are completed Mr. Palmisano ex\npert* (o introduce them in the House.\nI don\u2019t knov. of any more import\nant legislation that could be enacted\nfor the District at the special ses\nsion than these two bills.\" Mr. Palmi\nsano declared. \"They will give the\nDistrict at least an element of home\nrule.\"\nTile balance of the legislative pro\ngram. Mr. Palmisano said, will not\nbe determined until the full District\nCommittee holds its first meeting of\nthe new session November 24. A reg\nular meeting scheduled for Wednes\nday will not be held, he said, because\nhe has not had time to confer with\nthe members.\nPalmisano also plans to conler\nwith Speaker Bankhead and Maioritv\nLeader Rayburn before framing a\ncomprehensive program for the ses\nsion. He pointed out it would be\nunwise for the committee to report out\nsome of the numerous bills now before\nit unless there is likelihood of House\naction on them before the regular\nsession in January.\nSpeaker Bankhead already has an\nnounced the House would consider\nDistrict legislation during the special\nsession.\nNext Monday Is a regular \"District I\nday,\" but no decision has been reached\nwhether the three local bills on the\ncalendar will be considered at that\ntime.\nOne of these measures would estab\nlish a five-day. 60-hour week in the\nFire Department. Another would per\nmit retirement of police and firemen\nat the age of 60 after 25 years of\nservice. The third is designed to reg\nulate and control barber shops.\nI\nRadio Plea Climaxes Weeks\nof Organization for Volun\ntary Count of Jobless.\nThe text of President Roosevelt's\nfireside chat appears on\npage B-2.\nBr I he A.&ocieied Press.\nA plea from President Roosevelt\nrallied all citizens todav to help the\nGovernment find out this week the\nnumber and location of the unem-\nployed.\nClimaxing weeks of organization for\nthe voluntary census of the unem-1\nployed, the President appealed last\nmglit in a radio address for the sup\nport of all interested in finding a\n\"permanent cure\" for unemployment.\n\"The permanent cure.\u201d he said, \"lies\nin finding suitable jobs in indu.strv and\nagriculture for all willing workers.\nThai is a long and difficult\nproblem to find the answer to and it1\nmav take msnv efforts in the coming\nyears to find the right answer. Bill\nin the meantime we need more facts.\"\nAlthough only those unemployed or\npartially employed are to return the\ncensus cards, which will be distrib\nuted tomorrow by 150.000 postmen to\niverv home in the United States, the\nPresident said:\n\"I appeal to all of you who are\nemployed today to enlist as good\nneighbors to those who are unem- j\nployed in your communities and who\nmay need helo in filling out their\ncards properly and promptly,\u201d he\nsaid.\nThe mechanics of the census, worked\nout by John D. Biggers. Toledo lOhioi\nbusiness man. provide for distribution\nof 85.000,000 cards asking 14 ques\ntions.\nThe card* are to be returned, postage\nfree, by Saturday. When their answers\nhave been compiled the Government\nexpects to know, besides the number\nof unemployed: Their ages, where\nthey live and what sort of work they\nare qualified to do.\nThe President indicated he consid\nered this Jast topic of great im\nportance, that there may be \"co\noperative effort and planning which\nwill lead to the absorption of this\nunused manpower in private industry.\"\nSummary of Today's Star\np*8<\u201c Page. I\nAmusements B-*\u00ab Sports A-14-15-1C\nComics B-1S-19 Radio B-14\nEditorials A-l* Short Story .B-14\nFinance A-17 Society_B-l\nlost* Found B-14 Woman Pg. B-l*\nObituary A-l*\nFOREIGN.\nBrussels parley approves criticism of\nTolcio. Page A.|\nJapanese devastate Soochow as Nan\nking drive starts. Page A-*\nPower* seen blaming U. S. if Brus\nsels talk fails. Page A-*\nJapanese seek U. S. money for Man\nchukuo exploitation. Page B-S\nNATIONAL.\nPresident rallies citisens to jobless\ncensus. Page A.,\nRoosevelt urges Congress to remove tax\ninjustices. Page A-l\nCoast Guard cutter Apache to be de\ncommissioned soon. Page A-I\nPresident turns attention to budget\nmessage. Page A-l\nMcCarran to seek *1,500 minimum for\nU. S. employes. Page A-l\nWASHINGTON AND T1CINITT.\nPalmisano to push civil service plan\nfor city employes. Pa|e A-l\nCommunity Chest workers to report\ntoday. Page A-l\nAppeaU Court holds snow removal\nparking ban is valid. Page A-l\nHousing prospects to be discussed at\nmeetings here. Page A-*\nThree killed, score injured in week end\ntraffic. Page B-l\nNew regulations in effect today at\nWashington Airport. Page B-l\nTown Hall speaker sound* warning\nto democracies. Page B-l\nA\nEDITORIAL AND COMMENT.\nEditorials. Page A-l# j\nThis and That. Page A-l#\nAnswer* to Questions. Page A-l#\nWashington Observations. Page A-lt\nDavid Lawrence. Page A-ll\nH. R. Baulchage. Page A-ll\nDorothy Thompson. Page A-ll\nConstantine Brown. Page A-ll\nLemuel Parton. Page A-ll\nMISCELLANY.\nCity News in Brief. Page A-<\nShipping News. Page A-t\nBedtime Stories. Page B-5\nDorothy Dix. Page B-12\nBetsy Caswell. Page B-12\nNature's Children. Page B-14\nCroas-word Puxxle. Page B-lt\nLetter*Out. Page B-IS\nWinning Contract. Page B-lt\nSPORTS.\nPitt, Fordham, California, 'Bama lead\ngrid parade. Page A-14\nHoyt surprise choice for boss of\nA. A. U. Page A-14\nRedskins bow to Pirate* as Giants also\nare downed. Page A-14\nPan interest high in G. U.-Terp tilt\nhere Saturday. Page A-1S\nMob on rampage ruin* Montague\ncharity golf show. Page A-1C\nFINANCIAL.\nRail bonds Improve (table). Page A-l*\nDry good* trade declines. Page A-17\nStocks rise quietly (table). Page A-l*\nCurb utilities higher (table). Page A-lt\n8teel rate still drops. Page A-lt\nColumbian Carbon net gains.\nPage A-lt\nI.\nIncomes Under j\n$5,000 Would\nBe Exempt.\ni\n$7,000,000 LOSS\nIN TAXES SEEN\nHouse Unit Mav\nJ\nExtend Aid to Up\nper Braekets.\nBe the Associsi.d Press.\nA House tax subcommittee tenta\ntively agreed today to exempt all cor\nporations having *5.000 net income j\nor lea.* from the undistributed profits\ntax.\nChairman Vinson. Democrat, of\nKentucky, in announcing this step to\nmeet growing demands for tax relief\nfor business, said it would applv to\ntwo-thirds ot the corporations which\nhave a net income.\nA loss of some *1.000 000 in annual\nrevenue will result. Vinson said.\n\"The committee.\" he added, \"is\nstill considering added relief pro\nvisions for ootpotations having net\nincome of more than *5 000 and ex\ntending up to a bracket not yet tenia-\nlively agreed on. But the limit will\nbe at leas' *50.000 net income or\nmore.\"\nlaMM Carryover Allowed.\nThese additional means of easing the I\ntax burden of business, he said, also\nwere decided upon tentatively:\nAllowing a carryover of operating\nlosses for one year, to be applied\nagainst adjusted net income in the\nfollowing year in arriving at the basis\nfor the undistributed profits tax.\nThus, if a corporation had a net\noperating loss of *100 this year and a\nnet income of S100 next year, he ex\nplained. the firm would have to pay\nno undistributed earnings levy\u2014-only\nthe normal corporation tax.\nThe loss from this relief provision\nwould be several million dollars, he\nestimated.\nWage Bill Petition Une.\nA proposal to help firms in the\ndeficiency assessment field, which\ntvotild work out this wav:\nIf a corporation has submitted a\n*5.000 reduction from the undistrib\nuted profits tax in one year and ihe\ndeduction finally is disallowed, the\nAim would ha\\e GO or 90 davs after\nthe final determination in which to\ndeclare *5.000 in dividends. For the\nyear in which the determination was\nmade, Vinson said, the corporation\nthus could be relieved of paying an\nundistributed profits tax on an addi\ntional *5.000 ion which it had not\ncounted.\nChairman Norton Democrat, }>f\nNew Jersey of the House Labor Com\nmittee said today she would file soon\na petition lo lake the administration\u2019s\nwage-hour bill away from the Rules\nCommittee. The latter committee\nbottled up the legislation last ses\nsion.\n\"I will file the petition today, if it\nis ready in time.\" she said.\nMrs. Norton will confer late today\nwith Speaker Bankhead and other\nleaders to decide what the procedure\nwill be to press the measure to enact\nment.\nPARK MAY FORM\nRITCHIE MEMORIAL\nChairman of Committee Says It\nWill Be Placed Near\nAnnapolis.\nSpecial Dispatch to Tha Star.\nANNAPOLIS, Nov. 15.\u2014Stuart S.\nJanney, sr., chairman of the Ritchie\nMemorial Committee, today announced\nthat the Ritchie Memorial would be\nplaced In the vicinity of Annapolis.\nMr. Janney said the committee had\nabout (40,000 in funds to spend.\nThe chairman said he could not\ndiscuss plans for hte memorial just\nnow, but intimated that it might take\nthe form of a park.\nThe plans are being worked out\nwith State officials, he said, and it is\nexpected they will be announced in\nthe near future.\nSoon after the death of Gov. Ritchie\nthe Maryland Legislature authorized\nthe naming of a committee to raise\nfunds for the project.\nMembers Learn\nOf New Session\nFrom Hearsay\nBy th* Associated Press.\nTechnically speaking, the second ses\nsion of the Seventy-fifth Congress as\nsembled today on pure hearsay.\nIt sounds strange, but\u2014\nNobody sent the members any notice\nto appear.\n\u201cThey just see the President's proc\nlamation in a newspaper.\" explained\nHouse Parliamentarian Lewis Deadl\nier, \"Or, if they miss/it, some one tells\nthem about It.\u201d\nThis system, which would make\nsome American business men scream\nfor an efficiency expert, has been\ngoing on without serious complications\nfor generations.\na\n/saxyouVe\\\nCtOT M V;\n\\ty\u00abTERMCK!/\nItaly Votes \u201cNo\u201d\u2014Brussels\nDelegates Adjourn Till\nNov. 22.\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nBrussels conference of signatories\nand adherents of nine power treaty\nguaranteeing administrative and\nterritorial integrity 01 China met\nNovember J. but so far has been\nunable to discover basis for peace\nnegotiations in Far Bast, os Jupan\ntwice refused to attend sessions.\nItaly a stumbling block in path of\nsubstantial achievement by parley.\nSaturday draft declaration mildly\ncriticizing Jupan /or policies was\nadopted.\nB9 (he Assoc (a led Press.\nBRUSSELS Nov. 15\u2014A declara\ntion summarizing the Far Eastern con\nflict and criticizing Japan was adopted\nlodav by the Brussels Conference, with\nItaly voting \"no.'\u2019 and three Scan\ndinavian countries abstaining.\nThe Italian delegate. Count Luigi\nAldrovandi-M&rescotti, said ttial he\nmust vole against the summary be\ncause Italy believed it presages a\ncourse which can lead only to com\nplications.\nAdjourns Till Nov. !t.\nThe conference voted against send\ning a copy of the declaration to the\nJapanese government, then adjourned\nuntil Nov. 22.\nThe declaration was prepared by\nthe United States, British and French\ndelegates.\nAdjournment enables the chairman.\nForeign Minister Paul Spaalt of Bel\ngium, to accompany King Leopold on\na state visit to London tomorrow.\nAdjournment also gave Japan\na third and final chance to make some\nconciliatory gesture before the start\nof the second phase of the confer\nence\u2014probably discussion of the ap\npeal of the Chinese delegate. Dr. V.\nK. Wellington Koo, for direct aid to\nChina.\nDelegates Pessimistic.\nWith a breathing spell ahead during\nwhich Tokio has another chance to\nthink it over, delegates looked to the\nEast without optimism for some hint\nof a friendly gesture by warring\nJapan.\nIn this connection it was disclosed\nthat M. Spaak was considering the\npossibility of instructing the Belgian\nAmbassador to Tokio to make confl\nderftial inquiry seeking a clarification\nof a sentence in Japan's second re\nfusal to participate in conference pro\nceedings. The sentence referred to\nthe \u2018contribution\u201d toward settlement\nof the conflict which could be made\nby other powers.\n__\nJudge Condones\nStealing to Live;\nReleases Three\nA mother ancf her two daughter*\ncharged with .shoplilting were released\non-then personal bona by Police Court\nJudge Edward M. Curran today in a\ngesture of sympathy for their un-\nfavorable circumstances in life\nThe three were arrested after they\nallegedly stole a number of articles\nfrom three downtown department\nstores. The court was informed that\nthe mother and one daughter, both\nfrom Roanoke. Va.. had come here\nto visit another aaughler whose hus\nband has just been released from a\nhospital. All were without funds.\nIn releasing them Judge Curran\nsaid that, while it was necessary for\npolice U> bring them Into court, he\nbelieved \"There are times wtien per\nsons are forced to violate the law in\nolder to live.\"\n\"I feel it would be unjust to eiiher\nsend you to jail or place you on pro\nbation.\u201d he continued. \u2019I am releas\ning you so you may again become the\nhonorable citizens which you have ap\nparently been up to this time.\nBLACK CHALLENGES\nREFUSED BY COURT\nFlorida Corporations Lose in\nMove to Force Heatings of\nCases.\nBy ih* Associated Pres*\nThe Supreme Court turned back to\nday three new challenges directed\nagainst, the eligibility of Justice Hugo\nL. Black to serve on the tribunal.\nThree Florida corporations lost in\ntheir second effort to gain a rehear\ning of litigation on the ground that\nBlack was not qua lifted to sit in\njudgment.\nThe tribunal denied the petition for\nrehearing and suggestion of disquali\nfication filed by the Ryan Florida\nCorp and others.\nThey protested against efforts of\nthe Securities Commission to obtain\ntheir telegrams. contending that\nBlack, when chairman of the Senate\nLobby Committee had favored similar\naction.\nThe court also denied a motion by\nElizabeth L. Seymour of Salamanca.\nN. Y., and Robert Gray Taylor ol\nMedia. Pa., for permission to file a\nbrief \"containing certain allegations\naffecting the legality of the oath\"\ntaken by Black.\nTaylor described himself as chair\nman of the Philadelphia Court Plan\nCommittee.\nTyphoon Dead 35.\nMANILA, Nov. 15 <j<Pt.\u2014Known\ndeaths in Thursday's typhoon reached\n35 today.\nSnow Removal Parking Ban\nUpheld by Court of Appeals\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nCommissioners finally abandoned\nefforts to enforce ban on early\nmorning parking last winter after\ntwo regulations, designed to facili\ntate removal of snow from the\nstreets, were held \u201cunreasonable\nand inttalid\" by Police Court Judge\nEdward M. Curran. Judge Curran\nheld one such parking ban illegal\non January 26 and ruled out. a\nsubstitute on February 27. The\nlatter case was carried to the\nUnited States Circuit Court of\nAppeals.\nBy WILLIAM S. TARVER.\nIn a strongly worded opinion recog\nnising broad powers in the District\nCommissioners to regulate or ban\nstreet parking, the United States\nCourt of Appeals today upheld the\nvalidity of the regulation promulgated\nlast year banning parking on down\ntown streets from 2 a.m. to t a.m.\nduring the winter, which the Police\nCourt had previously declared un\nreasonable add void.\nThe decision restores the effective\nness of the regulation, which was de\nsigned to facilitate snow removal be\ntween December' 15 and March It.\nI\nOn motion of counsel for Z. Mot\nford Smith, a motorist who had been\ncharged with violation of the regu\nlation a Police Court judge some\nmonths ago held that the regulation\nwas unreasonable since it applied\nwithout regsid to whether snow was\nactually present on the streets.\n\"This contention is wholly without\nmerit,\" said Asdbciale Justice D. Law\nrence Oroner, speaking for the court.\n\"The removal of snow will be alto\ngether obstructed or at least seriously\nhampered by the presence of automo\nbiles parked along the curb; and this,\nwe think, Is enough to Justify the\nregulation.\u201d\nHe stated that Congress had validly\ndelegated authority to the Commis\nsioners to make and enforce \u201creason\nable rules for safe and convenient use\nof the streets for public travel.\u201d\nIndicating *the court believes the\nCommissioners may exercise wide dis\ncretion under this delegation of au\nthority, the court said the delega\ntion \"necessarily includes the right to\nrestrict the parking of cars on the\npublic street whenever such parking\ninterferes unreasonably either with\nthe use of the streets for the purposes\n(See PARKING, Page A-S~)\nft\nCHEST DRIVE TOTAL!\nRISES TDJ7185*\nrer ueru 01 uoai is\nRaised\u2014Number Aiding\nDrive Is 50,041.\nReporting collection? of *187.445.96\nover the week end. the Community\nChest campaign organization raised\nits total to date to *718.546.51. which 1\nis 34,89 per cent of this years goal\nThe number of contributor.? was\nincreased by 14.169 over the week end\nto a total of 50.041.\nThe organizai ion luncheon in the\nWillard Hotel ballroom was presided\nover bv H. L. Rust, jr., chairman for\n(he day.\nPresident Clarence Phelps Dodge 1\not the Chest called the meeting to\nOlder and then turned it ovei to Mr.\nRust. Joseph D. i Radio Joe> Kauf\nman. chairman of the Publicity Unit,\nhad prepared a number of surprises\nfor the volmateers. designed To \"pep\nthem up\" to poutinue to carrv on an\nintensive campaign until the close No\nvember 23.\nProm all sections of the city today\ncame reports indicating that the\nworkers, especially those of the Mei\nlopolitan. Suburban and Capital\nUnits, took advantage of the pleasant\nweek-end weather to solicit the resi\ndential quarters of the city.\nGolf clubs remained in their bags. 1\nauto trips into the countryside were\nsacrificed and some of the workers\neven missed church in their efforts\nto achieve then quotas. Chest officials\nsa id.\nZeal of Workers Hailed.\n\"No one could be skeptical in re\ngard to the outcome of this campaign\nafter seeing the zeal with which these\nworkers, nearly 9.000 of them, are\nfacing their task,\" Mr. Dodge said\n\"Their spirit, their willingness to\ngive long hours snd effort to this cause, j\nin addition to making substantial con-\ntributions on their own parts, their\nwillingness to come to meetings, pav\nfor their own luncheons and. as has\nbeen the case at the first two meetings\nfor a part of them, stand without\nluncheon In order to know what is be\ning done, gives us all confidence that\nthe Chest is going to achieve its goal\nof $2,059,000!\u2019\u2019\nChest officials today reported receipts\nof two gifts of unsual character, each\n$1. One came from Mrs. Lillian Bot\nkin. 1445 N street N.W.. one of the\nfew women cab drivers in Washington,\nwho knows at first hand the value of\nthe Chest as she was aided during a\nserious illness last year.\nWidow Donates $1.\nThe second $1 contribution came\nthrough Envoy Pattie Orimshaw,\nmatron of the Salvation Armv'j Wom\nens Emergency Home at 622 Sixth\nstreet N.W. It was donated by a\nwidow who had applied for assistance\nto the Salvation' Army some time ago\nwhen she had no money. She was\nkept in the home for several days\nand. finally, after she obtained a\nsmall-paying job. she sent her con\ntribution to the Chest to aid others\nin similar circumstances.\nChest contributors will be given an\nopportunity to hear just exactly how\ntheir donations are spent tonight\nwhen the first of a series of broad\ncasts directly from agencies financed\nthrough the Chest will be presented.\nStation WJSV Is putting on the\nseries, with Announcer Hugh Conover\ndirecting, and the first one is sched\nuled for 6:30 p.m. Mr. Conover will\nInterview children and others at the\nvarious institutions and agencies.\nThe message of the Chest will come\nfrom the skies Wednesday night when\na transport plane bearing a Chest\nspeaker will fly over the city.\nThrough the co-operation of Penn\nsylvania-Central Airlines Corp. and\nthe National Broadcasting Co., the\nspeaker's discussion of the needs of\nthe Chest will be broadcast over Sta\ntion WMAL by meahs of a remote\ncontrol transmitter In the plane.\nOrange Matter Re-elected.\nHARRISBURG. Pa.. Nov. IS\nLouie J. Taber of Colombo*, Ohio, wm\nre-elected mauler of the National\nOrana* today for bit eiyhtb term.\nI\nMAYOR LA GUARDIA\nPREDICTS WINTER\nINCREASE IN IDLE\nMore U. S. Funds Will Be\nNeeded, He Asserts at\nConference Here.\nDEFENDS MUNICIPALITIES\nFOR THEIR RELIEF SHARE\nNew Yorker Lays Business Timid\nity to \"Those Who Are Ballvhoo\ning Another Depression.\"\nBv J. A. FOX.\nA prediction that the winter wilt\nbring increased unemployment and\nnecessitate an inctease in Federal relief\nfunds was made today by Mavor F H\nLa Guaidia of New York City, opening\nthe annual United Slates Conference\nof Mayors.\nAddressing ti\u00ab? tlief executives of\nmore than luu cities gathered in the.\nMayflower Hotel, the New York Mavor.\nwho is preside